# LPC2129 UART Driver (Bare-Metal Embedded C)

## Overview
This project demonstrates a **bare-metal UART driver implementation for the LPC2129 (ARM7) microcontroller** using Embedded C. The driver is developed using **direct register-level programming** without any external libraries.

The main objective of this project is to understand how UART communication works at the hardware level, including initialization, baud rate configuration, data transmission, and reception.

---

## Features
- UART0 initialization on LPC2129 (ARM7)
- Baud rate configuration using system clock
- 8-bit data frame format (1 stop bit, no parity)
- Polling-based data transmission and reception
- Basic error detection using Line Status Register (LSR)
- Simple echo-based UART communication

---

## Hardware Used
- LPC2129 ARM7 Microcontroller
- UART serial interface
- keil version 4

---

## Working Principle

### UART Initialization
- Configures UART0 pins using PINSEL register
- Sets data format to 8-bit, 1 stop bit, and no parity

### Baud Rate Configuration
- Baud rate is generated using system clock division formula:
  - Baud Rate = PCLK / (16 × Divisor)
- Divisor is loaded into DLL and DLM registers

### Data Transmission
- Checks Transmit Holding Register (THR) status
- Sends data byte when transmitter is ready

### Data Reception
- Waits until Receive Buffer Register (RBR) has valid data
- Reads incoming byte from UART
- Checks Line Status Register (LSR) for errors

---

## Functionality Flow
1. Initialize UART0 peripheral  
2. Configure baud rate (e.g., 9600)  
3. Send a test character  
4. Receive a character from serial terminal  
5. Echo received character back if no error is detected  

